    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="669"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d669">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5034 Business Tax/62</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1888</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-24">December 24,
                            1932</date>.<lb/>[Received January 30, 1933.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With further reference to the Legation’s despatch
                    No. 1871, December 21, 1932, regarding the attempts of the Chinese authorities
                    to enforce the business tax upon American firms, I have the honor to enclose
                    copies of the memorandum of a conversation I had on December 17th with M.
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHA1">Wilden</persName>, the French
                    Minister, and Mr. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_IEMB1">Ingram</persName>, the
                    British Chargé d’Affaires.<note n="64" xml:id="d669fn64">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I informed my colleagues that, while we were protesting against the collection of
                    this tax upon American firms, we were not endeavoring to prevent American
                    merchants from dealing with the matter in any practical manner they might deem
                    advisable.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Trusler Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
